  "prompt": "Is it OK if I copy-paste code while solving competitive programming problems?",
  "response": "Here's a balanced perspective on copying code in competitive programming:\n\n1. During Practice/Learning:\n- It's acceptable and often helpful to learn from others' solutions\n- Study and understand the code you're copying\n- Try to rewrite the solution in your own words\n- Learn the underlying algorithm/technique\n\n2. During Actual Competitions:\n- Copying code is considered cheating\n- Most platforms have strict plagiarism checks\n- You should write your own solutions\n- Penalties can include disqualification\n\n3. Ethical Approaches:\n- Study standard algorithms and templates beforehand\n- Practice implementing solutions yourself\n- Use copied code as a learning reference, not a direct submission\n- Develop problem-solving skills independently\n\n4. Best Practices:\n- Understand the logic behind solutions\n- Practice implementing algorithms from scratch\n- Build a personal code library through genuine learning\n- Focus on problem-solving skills, not just quick solutions\n\n5. Learning Resources:\n- Competitive programming websites\n- Algorithm tutorials\n- Practice coding challenges\n- Online judge platforms\n\nThe goal is to improve your skills, not just solve problems quickly.",
